        <section xml:id="Section_2_2">
        <title>Section 2.2</title>
        
            
<subsection xml:id="Question_2">
<title> Question 2</title>

<p>
    Suppose <m>n=6k+5</m>. Then, <m>n=3(2k)+3+2=3(2k+1)+2</m> and so <m>n</m> is of the form <m>3j+1</m> where <m>j=2k+1</m>.

    Conversely, for example, <m>m=3 \cdot 0+1=3</m> is not of the form <m>6k+5</m> since <m>6k+5=3</m> has no integer solutions.
</p>

       
</subsection>

<subsection sml:id="Question_3">
    <title>Question 3</title>

    <p>
        By the division algorithm, any integer, <m>n</m>, is of the form <m>3k</m>, <m>3k+1</m>, or <m>3k+2</m>.

        Square each of these cases:
        <md>
            <mrow>(3k)^2 \amp =9k^2=3(3k^2) </mrow>
            <mrow>(3k+1)^2 \amp = 9k^2+6k+1=3(3k^2+2k)+1 </mrow>
            <mrow>(3k+2)^2 \amp = 9k^2+12k+4=3(3k^2+4k+1)+1.</mrow>
        </md>
      So the square of any integer is of the form <m>3j</m> or <m>3j+1.</m>  
    </p>
</subsection>
    
    

